    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe not the right topic, but not sure if there is one. Just looked at a paper which showed that  a number of theorems implied one another. I realized, in general, I don't know what that actually means (in this case there were reduction results about procedures, so it made some sense). It is possible for conjectures to imply one another, or axioms to imply one another. I.e. one can show that \"if one holds, all hold\". But once something is a theorem, then it is a tautology, right? So all theorems which hold in a given axiomatic setup in some sense \"imply\" one another. Constructivism alone doesn't suffice to resolve this problem, if we keep proofs as \"mere propositions\". However, perhaps in HoTT we can have a \"higher\" notion of implication where if we don't have 0-truncated proofs, but rather proofs with meaningful content, then there's a further way to characterize this? Would it be exhibiting a full isomorphism between the proofs-as-genuine-functions? Is there any paper or work that discusses this problem further? It seems like a classic thing that philosophers would ponder...</p>",
        "id": 195127541,
        "sender_full_name": "Gershom",
        "timestamp": 1587681025
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>reminds me of a note in one of andrej bauer's papers... one sec</p>",
        "id": 195129878,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1587682861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/9HBDTSIajaeRrqHL8Mq6uSPc/image.png\" title=\"image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/9HBDTSIajaeRrqHL8Mq6uSPc/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/9HBDTSIajaeRrqHL8Mq6uSPc/image.png\"></a></div>",
